Removing Outlier¶

In [6]:
def Zscore_outlier(df, colmn):
    out = []
    m = np.mean(df)
    sd = np.std(df)
    for i in df: 
        z = (i-m)/sd
        if np.abs(z) > 3 : 
            out.append(i)
    print("Outliers at {}: ".format(colmn),out)
    return out

        df = df.drop(index = i)

A) Largest K¶

  • Length of n samples (data_set) is 690
  • where k should be < sqrt(690) so we iterate to find best k with best CV

In [23]:
def make_K_odd(k):
    if int(k) % 2 == 0: #even
        return (int(k) - 1)
    else:
        return int(k)
In [24]:
# K < sqrt(n)

B) iterate with diff combinations of CV and K to reach largest Recall¶

Method 1 by For loop¶

In [25]:
#to chose K that make largest recall
largest = 0
k = 0
index = 0
df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["k","recall"])
for i in range (1,largrest_k + 1, 2): 
    knn_classifer = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = i, p=2, metric='euclidean') #p = 2 if he death or not)
    y_train_predict = cross_val_predict(knn_classifer, knn_train_corona, Ytrain, cv=10) #(fit + predictions) 
    my_call = recall_score(Ytrain, y_train_predict) # TP / (p = (TP + FN))
    #print(my_call)
    #cv_r2_scores_rf = cross_val_score(knn_classifer, knn_train_corona, Ytrain, cv=10) #(fit + score(acc)) 
    df.loc[index, 'k'] = i
    df.loc[index,'recall'] = my_call
    index = index + 1
    #find maximum recall
    if  my_call > largest:
        largest = my_call
        k = i 
print(df)
print("biggest recall:", largest, ",at k =", k)

'''
we have 3 hyperparams that affect the most on knn
k = range(1, largest_k, 2)
knn weights
dist
'''

model = KNeighborsClassifier() #model it's self


range_k = list(range(1, largrest_k, 2)) #range of k values that move by odd numbers

# all possible hyperparameters
model_params = { 'n_neighbors' : range_k,
               'weights' : ['uniform','distance'],
               'metric' : ['minkowski','euclidean','manhattan']}

sub_model = GridSearchCV(model, model_params, cv = 10, scoring = 'f1', n_jobs = -1, verbose = 1)

# Fit the grid
sub_model.fit(knn_train_corona, Ytrain)

print("Best cross-validation score: {:.2f}".format(sub_model.best_score_))
print("Best parameters: \n{}".format(sub_model.best_params_))

A) Tuning Hyperparameters of Logistic Regression using for-loops¶

In [39]:
cc = [0.01 , 0.1 , 1 , 10 , 100 , 1000 , 1e4 , 1e5 , 1e6 ]   #size = 9
solver = ['liblinear' , 'newton-cg' , 'lbfgs']               #size = 3

nfold = 10
accm = np.zeros(27)
precm = np.zeros(27)
recm = np.zeros(27)
f1m = np.zeros(27)

# Compute the standard errors
prec_se = np.zeros(27)
rec_se = np.zeros(27)
f1_se = np.zeros(27)
acc_se = np.zeros(27)

ii = 0
for c in cc:
    for sol in solver:
        kf = KFold(n_splits=nfold)
        acc = np.zeros(nfold)
        prec = np.zeros(nfold)
        rec = np.zeros(nfold)
        f1 = np.zeros(nfold)
        kf = KFold(n_splits=nfold)
        kf.get_n_splits(xtr)
        i = 0
        
        for all_except_index, fold_index in kf.split(xtr):
            
            testX = xtr[fold_index]
            testY = ytr[fold_index]
            trainX = xtr[all_except_index]
            trainY = ytr[all_except_index]    
            # Scale the data
            scal = StandardScaler()
            trainX_ = scal.fit_transform(trainX)
            testX_ = scal.transform(testX)    
            # Fit a model
            reg = linear_model.LogisticRegression(solver=sol , C=c)
            reg.fit(trainX_, trainY)
            # Predict on test samples and measure accuracy
            yhat = reg.predict(testX_)
            acc[i] = np.mean(yhat == testY)
            # Measure other performance metrics
            prec[i],rec[i],f1[i],_  = precision_recall_fscore_support(testY,yhat,average='binary')
            i = i + 1
            
        # Take average values of the metrics
        precm[ii] = np.mean(prec)
        recm[ii] = np.mean(rec)
        f1m[ii] = np.mean(f1)
        accm[ii] = np.mean(acc)
        
        # Compute the standard errors
        prec_se[ii] = np.std(prec)/np.sqrt(nfold-1)
        rec_se[ii] = np.std(rec)/np.sqrt(nfold-1)
        f1_se[ii] = np.std(f1)/np.sqrt(nfold-1)
        acc_se[ii] = np.std(acc)/np.sqrt(nfold-1)
        ii = ii + 1
        
        
# print(accm)
print(accm.max())
print(accm.argmax())

# print(recm)
print(recm.max())
print(recm.argmax())

The goodness of a classification method is often measured by the area under the curve (AUC), which is independent of the threshold. A method with a higher AUC means that under the same FPR, it has higher PPR. Note that in practice, you should evalute UAC in different cross validation folds and then evaluate the mean AUC.

'''
we have 3 hyperparams that affect the most on tree
'criterion'
'max_depth'
'min_samples_leaf'
'''

model = DecisionTreeClassifier() #model it's self




max_depth_range = list(range(1, 8, 1))
min_samples_leaf_range = list(range(3, 6, 1))

# all possible hyperparameters


model_params = { 'criterion' : ['gini', 'entropy'],
               'max_depth' : max_depth_range,
                'min_samples_leaf' : min_samples_leaf_range,
               }


# n_jobs=1 means how many parallel threads to be executed.
# verbose=1 means print the model fitting details, the higher the value, the more the details printed.
sub_model = GridSearchCV(model, model_params, cv = 10, scoring = 'recall', n_jobs = -1, verbose = 1)

# Fit the grid
sub_model.fit(xtr_norm, ytr)

print("Best cross-validation score: {:.2f}".format(sub_model.best_score_))
print("Best parameters: \n{}".format(sub_model.best_params_))

Fitting 10 folds for each of 42 candidates, totalling 420 fits
Best cross-validation score: 0.84
Best parameters: 
{'criterion': 'entropy', 'max_depth': 6, 'min_samples_leaf': 4}

please note There is alot of combinations have same maximum but i chosed one with 6 and 4

Best HyperParameters for this range of features is

criterion : entropy, max_depth: 6, min_samples_leaf: 4

'''
we have 3 hyperparams that affect the most on SVM
'gamma' #i used auto or scale
'kernel'# i left it to be chosen by mode itself
'C' 
'''

model = SVC() #model it's self

# gammas = [1,0.1,0.01,0.001,0.0001]      #size = 5
#i used auto or scale

# kernels = ['linear', 'poly', 'rbf', 'sigmoid']   #size = 4 'precomputed' is not used as it need square matrix
# i left it to be chosen by mode itself

cc = [0.1,1,10,100,1000]               #size = 5


# all possible hyperparameters
model_params = { 'gamma' : ['scale', 'auto'],
                 'C' : cc
               }


# n_jobs=1 means how many parallel threads to be executed.
# verbose=1 means print the model fitting details, the higher the value, the more the details printed.
sub_model = GridSearchCV(model, model_params, cv = 10, scoring = 'recall', n_jobs = -1, verbose = 1)

# Fit the grid
sub_model.fit(xtr_norm, ytr)

print("Best cross-validation score: {:.2f}".format(sub_model.best_score_))
print("Best parameters: \n{}".format(sub_model.best_params_))

Fitting 10 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 100 fits

Best parameters: 
{'C': 100, 'gamma': 'auto'}
